data.enText: the right to refuse to allow sth to be done, especially the right to stop a law from being passed or a decision from being taken

data.chText: 英国政府行使其否决权阻止了这项提案。
data.enText: The British government used its veto to block the proposal.
to have the power/right of veto
the use of the presidential veto
an occasion when sb refuses to allow sth to be done

data.chText: 有好几个月禁止雇用新职员。
data.enText: For months there was a veto on employing new staff.

data.chText: 行使否决权；拒绝认可；禁止
data.enText: to stop sth from happening or being done by using your official authority (= by using your veto )

data.chText: 修建大坝的计划已被环境保护局否决。
data.enText: Plans for the dam have been vetoed by the Environmental Protection Agency.
to refuse to accept or do what sb has suggested

data.chText: 我想去野营，但这个想法很快遭到了其他人的反对。
data.enText: I wanted to go camping but the others quickly vetoed that idea.

tr: a vote that blocks a decision
the power or right to prohibit or reject a proposed or intended act (especially the power of a chief executive to reject a bill passed by the legislature)

example: I forbid you to call me late at night
Mother vetoed the trip to the chocolate store

value.def: If someone in authority vetoes something, they forbid it, or stop it being put into action.

example.ex: De Gaulle vetoed Britain's application to join the EEC...
example.tran: 戴高乐驳回了英国加入欧洲经济共同体的申请。

example.ex: The President vetoed the economic package passed by Congress.
example.tran: 总统否决了国会通过的一揽子经济计划。

example.ex: The veto was a calculated political risk.
example.tran: 这项否决是一次精心策划的政治冒险。

value.def: Veto is the right that someone in authority has to forbid something.

trans: 一票否决权；否决权；有否决权；最后决定权；覆议权
